---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'What Is FICA? Social Security & Medicare Taxes Explained (2025)';
const description =
  'FICA explained in plain English: what the tax is, the Social Security and Medicare components and 2025 rates, the $176,100 wage base cap, the 0.9% Additional Medicare Tax, employer matching, and how it works if you are self-employed.';

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'What does FICA stand for?',
    a: 'FICA stands for the Federal Insurance Contributions Act. It is the payroll tax that funds Social Security and Medicare. When you see “FICA” on a pay stub, it refers to those two mandatory federal contributions taken out of your wages.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How much is FICA tax in 2025?',
    a: 'For most employees, FICA is 7.65% of your wages: 6.2% for Social Security plus 1.45% for Medicare. Your employer pays a matching 7.65%. The Social Security portion only applies to the first $176,100 of wages in 2025; Medicare has no wage cap.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is there a limit on how much FICA I pay?',
    a: 'The Social Security portion stops once your wages reach the $176,100 wage base for 2025, so the most Social Security tax an employee pays is $10,918.20. The Medicare portion has no cap and applies to every dollar you earn.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the Additional Medicare Tax?',
    a: 'High earners pay an extra 0.9% Medicare tax on wages above $200,000 (single) or $250,000 (married filing jointly). This surtax is paid by the employee only — employers do not match it — and it applies on top of the regular 1.45% Medicare rate.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Do self-employed people pay FICA?',
    a: 'Yes, but under a different name. The self-employed pay “self-employment tax,” which is both the employee and employer halves combined: 12.4% for Social Security plus 2.9% for Medicare, or 15.3% total. You can deduct half of it when figuring your income tax.',
  },
];

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })),
};

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'What Is FICA? Social Security & Medicare Taxes Explained',
  description,
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'EasyPayCalc' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'EasyPayCalc', url: 'https://easypaycalc.com' },
  mainEntityOfPage: 'https://easypaycalc.com/guides/what-is-fica',
};

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://easypaycalc.com' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Guides', item: 'https://easypaycalc.com/guides' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'What Is FICA', item: 'https://easypaycalc.com/guides/what-is-fica' },
  ],
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} schema={[articleSchema, faqSchema, breadcrumbSchema]}>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-12">
    <!-- Breadcrumb -->
    <nav class="text-sm text-slate-400" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-teal-700">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-1.5">/</span>
      <a href="/guides" class="hover:text-teal-700">Guides</a>
      <span class="mx-1.5">/</span>
      <span class="text-slate-600">What is FICA</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="mt-6">
      <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-xs font-semibold text-teal-700 bg-teal-100/80 ring-1 ring-teal-200 rounded-full px-3 py-1">
        <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500"></span> Updated for 2025
      </span>
      <h1 class="mt-5 text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 text-balance">
        What is FICA? Social Security &amp; Medicare taxes explained
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">
        Every paycheck, a chunk of your pay disappears into two letters most people never think about: FICA. Here is
        exactly what it is, how much it costs, and why it shows up on your pay stub.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-10 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">What FICA actually is</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          FICA stands for the <strong>Federal Insurance Contributions Act</strong>, the 1935 law that created the
          payroll taxes funding two of America&rsquo;s biggest social programs: <strong>Social Security</strong> and
          <strong>Medicare</strong>. When you see a line labeled &ldquo;FICA,&rdquo; &ldquo;OASDI,&rdquo; or
          &ldquo;Medicare&rdquo; on your pay stub, that money is being routed straight to these federal trust funds.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          FICA is not income tax. It is a separate, flat payroll tax that is taken out before you ever receive your
          money. Unlike federal income tax, it doesn&rsquo;t depend on your filing status or how many deductions you
          claim &mdash; nearly every working American pays the same percentage. It is also the reason your
          <a href="/" class="text-teal-600 font-medium underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">take-home pay</a>
          is noticeably smaller than your gross salary.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">The two halves of FICA</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          FICA is really two taxes bundled together. For a typical employee in 2025, they add up to
          <strong>7.65% of your wages</strong>:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Social Security tax &mdash; 6.2%.</strong> This funds retirement, disability, and survivor benefits. It only applies to wages up to an annual cap (the &ldquo;wage base&rdquo;).</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Medicare tax &mdash; 1.45%.</strong> This funds hospital insurance for people 65 and older. There is <em>no</em> cap &mdash; it applies to every dollar you earn.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Here is how the pieces break down for the 2025 tax year:
        </p>
        <div class="mt-5 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border border-slate-200 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
            <thead class="bg-slate-50 text-slate-500 text-left">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 font-semibold">Component</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 font-semibold">Employee rate</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 font-semibold">2025 wage cap</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-100">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium text-slate-800">Social Security (OASDI)</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5">6.2%</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5">Up to $176,100</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium text-slate-800">Medicare</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5">1.45%</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5">No cap (all wages)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium text-slate-800">Additional Medicare</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5">+0.9%</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5">Wages over $200k / $250k</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-teal-50/60"><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-semibold text-slate-900">Total (typical wages)</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-semibold text-slate-900">7.65%</td><td class="px-4 py-2.5">&mdash;</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-500">
          The employer pays a matching 6.2% + 1.45% on top of what you pay (the Additional Medicare Tax is the one
          exception &mdash; see below).
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">The Social Security wage base cap</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Social Security tax doesn&rsquo;t apply to unlimited income. In 2025, once your wages hit the
          <strong>$176,100 wage base</strong>, the 6.2% Social Security deduction stops for the rest of the year. That
          means the most Social Security tax any employee can pay in 2025 is <strong>$10,918.20</strong> (6.2% of
          $176,100).
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          If you earn more than the cap, you&rsquo;ll notice your paycheck actually gets a little bigger late in the
          year, because Social Security stops coming out. Medicare, however, keeps going &mdash; it never stops, no
          matter how high your income climbs.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">The Additional Medicare Tax for high earners</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          On top of the standard 1.45% Medicare rate, high earners owe an extra <strong>0.9% Additional Medicare
          Tax</strong> on wages above certain thresholds:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>$200,000</strong> if you file as single or head of household.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>$250,000</strong> if you are married filing jointly.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Two things make this surtax unusual. First, <strong>your employer does not match it</strong> &mdash; the full
          0.9% comes out of the employee&rsquo;s wages only. Second, employers are required to start withholding it once
          your pay from that job passes $200,000, regardless of your filing status, so married couples sometimes
          reconcile the exact amount when they file their annual return.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Employer matching &mdash; and self-employment</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          For every dollar of FICA you pay as an employee, your employer quietly pays a matching dollar. Your 6.2% + 1.45%
          is mirrored by the company&rsquo;s 6.2% + 1.45%, so a total of 15.3% is flowing to Social Security and Medicare
          on your wages &mdash; you just only see half of it on your stub.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          If you are <strong>self-employed</strong>, there is no employer to split the bill with, so you pay both halves
          yourself. This is called <strong>self-employment tax</strong>: 12.4% for Social Security (up to the same
          $176,100 cap) plus 2.9% for Medicare, for a combined <strong>15.3%</strong>. The trade-off is a break at tax
          time &mdash; the IRS lets you <strong>deduct half</strong> of your self-employment tax as an adjustment to
          income, roughly mirroring the portion an employer would have paid.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Where FICA shows up on your paycheck</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          On most pay stubs, FICA appears as one or two separate lines rather than a single &ldquo;FICA&rdquo; label.
          Look for entries like <strong>&ldquo;Social Security,&rdquo; &ldquo;SS,&rdquo; &ldquo;OASDI,&rdquo;</strong> or
          <strong>&ldquo;Fed OASDI/EE&rdquo;</strong> for the 6.2% piece, and <strong>&ldquo;Medicare&rdquo;</strong> or
          <strong>&ldquo;Fed MED/EE&rdquo;</strong> for the 1.45% piece. Together they explain a big share of the gap
          between your gross pay and what actually lands in your bank account.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Want to see the exact dollar amounts for your own salary? Our free
          <a href="/" class="text-teal-600 font-medium underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">paycheck calculator</a>
          breaks out Social Security, Medicare, federal, and state withholding so you can see precisely where your money
          goes each pay period.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <section id="faq">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-3">
          {faqs.map((f) => (
            <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white px-5 open:shadow-sm transition">
              <summary class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer list-none font-semibold text-slate-800 py-4">
                {f.q}
                <span class="ml-4 shrink-0 grid place-items-center w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-slate-100 text-slate-500 group-open:bg-teal-100 group-open:text-teal-700 group-open:rotate-45 transition">+</span>
              </summary>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed pb-5 -mt-1">{f.a}</p>
            </details>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="rounded-2xl bg-teal-50 border border-teal-100 p-6 text-center">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">See your FICA taxes on every paycheck</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Enter your salary to see Social Security, Medicare, and every other deduction broken out instantly.</p>
        <a href="/" class="mt-4 inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-xl bg-teal-600 text-white font-semibold px-5 py-3 hover:bg-teal-700 transition">Open the paycheck calculator →</a>
      </div>

      <!-- Related guides -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900">Related guides</h2>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2">
          <li><a href="/guides/how-to-read-your-pay-stub" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-800 underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">How to read your pay stub</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/gross-vs-net-pay" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-800 underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">Gross vs. net pay explained</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/pre-tax-deductions-401k-hsa" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-800 underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">Pre-tax deductions: 401(k) &amp; HSA</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 leading-relaxed border-t border-slate-100 pt-6">
        Disclaimer: This guide is for educational purposes only and does not constitute tax, legal, or financial advice.
        Tax rules and figures change and individual situations vary. Verify details with the IRS, the Social Security
        Administration, or a qualified tax professional before making decisions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
